I am Shilpi Soni, a space scientist and I am overjoyed to be helming the PMтАЩs social media properties on #WomensDay.

It is a leap forward for India towards achieving Aatmanirbharta in space technology. 

My current assignment includes serving as Associate Project Director for GSAT-22/23 communication payload to cater communication needs for IndiaтАЩs citizens. Earlier, I was fortunate to have been a part of the ISRO delegation to French Guyana, Kourou for the launch of GSAT. It gave me so much satisfaction to see the spacecraft being launched to space, in which I contributed along with a brilliant team.

user_info.Images[8].Caption:
Neem Karoli Baba's words, Love all. Feed all. Serve all. Remember God are a guiding force.

Love all means extending compassion without discrimination. ItтАЩs easy to love people who treat us well, but the deeper challenge is to love those who are difficult, different, or even unkind. Love is not about agreementтАФitтАЩs about recognising the divine in every being. It's about unconditional love. 

Feed all reminds us that nobody should go hungry. But hunger isnтАЩt only physical. People are also hungry for kindness, for connection, for hope. Feeding others means offering what we canтАФfood, time, encouragement, or simply presence.

Serve all is about humility. It means using our time and energy for the well-being of others. Service is not about status or recognition. ItтАЩs about doing what needs to be done, with sincerity and care.

Remember God grounds everything. ItтАЩs the call to stay inwardly connected while living outwardly engaged. To remember that behind every face, every act, and every moment, there is something sacred. We are all part of the divine. 

These words are not complicated. But living them fully transforms everything.

A woman wants to know if surrendering to God is the key to transmuting suffering in the world, and how that fits in with the message of Jesus on the cross.

Rupert says: тАШJesus first resolved the issue of resistance within himself and then he turned towards the world, sharing that understanding with the people who were torturing him. Because when he resolved the issue of resistance within himself a transmutation took place тАУ from sorrow to pure love.

тАШSimilarly youтАЩve surrendered your struggle with sorrow and you bear it in your heart.  And the reason you can bear it is because your heart is big enough тАУ not only for your personal sorrow тАУ but also humanityтАЩs sorrow. Just as your sorrow is ultimately not personal, your heart, whose nature is love, is also not personal. It is the heart of infinite being whose nature is love тАУ and that is what you are.тАЩ

Watch the full video on YouTube: https://youtu.be/pyckOdit3eg

In this conversation about the source of creation a woman asks about a passage from the Quran: тАШI was a hidden treasure and I loved to be known, so I created the world that I might be known.тАЩ What does it mean?

Rupert says: тАШWhat I think it means is that within consciousness, there is infinite treasure or potential which in consciousnessтАЩs experience of itself remains unmanifest. There is just the knowledge тАЬI amтАЭ тАУ no world, or objective experience. 

тАШBut at the same time, that тАЬI amтАЭ contains all knowledge and experience. ItтАЩs as if consciousness is pregnant with infinite potential тАУ and it has to be born. So the birth of the universe is the means by which that which lies in potential in consciousness is made manifest.тАЩ

Rupert mentions three recognitions regarding the nature of awareness: you are the witness of experience, you are that in which experience arises and you are one with experience. Why is the third recognition so much more difficult to grasp than the first two? 

Rupert says: тАШThe reason why itтАЩs relatively easy to understand the first two is that neither of them contradict the evidence of sense-perception. But the last recognition does. It completely shatters our conventional materialistic view of the world. 

тАШAnd even when we understand this clearly, sense-perception still tells us the world is outside of our self, separate from our self, made out of something other than our self тАУ and our understanding has to override that.тАЩ

user_info.Images[0].Caption:
When I was a child playing cricket in the fields in Punjab, I had one dream. A dream to represent my country. In 2018, by Gods grace, I received my India Cap Number 75 in the T20i team and Cap Number 221 in the ODI team.

The time has now come to call time on my career in India and announce my retirement.

Words cannot express my gratitude for the love and support I have received through all the highs and lows of my career. I want to thank God for the path that has been made for me; the fans for the endless support; my parents and family for the sacrifices and confidence you have given me, especially during the injuries and lows; my teammates over the years for the dressing room memories and friendships; the BCCI for fulfilling a young childтАЩs dream to represent India and win the 2008 Under-19 World Cup and receive my T20i and ODI caps in 2018!
Kolkata Knight Riders , Delhi Daredevils, Sunrisers Hyderabad and Royal Challengers Bangalore IPL franchises for giving me memories of a lifetime; and last but not least, the @pcacricketassociation for giving me an opportunity to make my First Class debut in 2007 and supporting me throughout my career. Without all your support I would not be the person I am today.

I donтАЩt know what the future holds but I look back on this chapter with only fond memories and now on to the next chapter. 

Once again, thank you

Siddharthh Kaul 
(Sid Kaul)

user_info.Biography: Uncovering the world of Patek Philippe, the last independent, family-owned Genevan watch manufacture. Welcome. #PatekTime
user_info.Images[0].Caption:
The historic desk clocks made in the 1920s for renowned collectors James Ward Packard and Henry Graves Jr. are feature both key-winding and setting. Each clock features a 24тАЩтАЩтАЩ eight-day going movement and seven horological complications. On top of the date of the month, day of the week and month of the year, the complications include a perpetual calendar with apertures, phases of the Moon, a four-year cycle of leap-years and an eight day power-reserve indication.

Both timepieces are housed in the Patek Philippe Museum, Geneva: Inv. P-140 (Packard) and Inv. P-1270 (Graves).

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMuseum #SuperComplications
user_info.Images[1].Caption:
In the early 1920s, Patek Philippe created two extraordinary desk clocks for renowned collectors James Ward Packard and Henry Graves Jr. respectively. Beyond their technical qualities and complications, the Packard clock (1923) and Graves clock (1927) stand as testaments to Patek Philippe's artistry with the hand-engraved details, painted numerals, metalwork and decorations.

These extraordinary pieces are part of the Patek Philippe Museum, Geneva: Inv. P-140 (Packard) and Inv. P-1270 (Graves).

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMuseum #SuperComplications
user_info.Images[2].Caption:
The great American collectors of the early twentieth century, James Ward Packard and Henry Graves Jr., are considered the most important individuals who changed the world of watch collecting. Packard was a self-made entrepreneur and inventor who was one of the pioneers of the automobile. Graves Jr., on the other hand, came from an affluent New York financial dynasty. 

They both commissioned specific timepieces based on their interests and personalities and, as such, challenged watchmakers. Among the myriad masterpieces created for these two collectors during the brief golden age was a wedge-shaped yellow gold and silver perpetual calendar moon-phase desk clock (Patek Philippe Museum, Geneva, Inv. No. P-140). It was delivered to James Ward Packard in 1923, and another almost identical model was sold by Tiffany & Co. to Henry Graves Jr. in 1927 (Patek Philippe Museum, Geneva, Inv. No. P-1270).

These historical timepieces are housed in the Patek Philippe Museum in Geneva.

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMuseum #SuperComplications
user_info.Images[3].Caption:
The Service Center in Beijing is part of a global network of Authorized Service Centers, each handpicked and accredited based on achieving and maintaining a level of service that adheres to strict quality criteria.

A fundamental part of what Patek Philippe does, customer service involves taking care of the customers as individuals, with unique needs, whilst maintaining consistency in providing the highest level of support.

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMaisons
user_info.Images[4].Caption:
The Maison Patek Philippe Beijing is located amid a historical enclave of consular residences at ChтАЩien Men, one of the cityтАЩs most renowned cradles of culture and the arts. It stands as a strong symbol of the brand as reflected by the Maison's Chinese name, тАЬYuan DiтАЭ (тАЬYuanтАЭ means origin in English and тАЬDiтАЭ is the translation of тАШMaisonтАЩ).

The fa├зade of the Maison maintains the neoclassical elegance of the building. The interior design, referencing the Patek Philippe Geneva Salons and the Maison Patek Philippe Shanghai, presents the brand's exquisite aesthetics and unique characteristics. The design creates a warm and welcoming atmosphere for guests to discover and experience the Patek Philippe collections.

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMaisons
user_info.Images[5].Caption:
In 2008, Patek Philippe expanded its presence in China by opening a boutique in Beijing and subsequently in 2014 the Maison Patek Philippe Beijing, echoing the boutique and maison combination present in Shanghai. Located in the heart of the capital, it quickly became a refined destination for watch connoisseurs. To further nurture this legacy, the brand crafted an elegant and welcoming space, inviting enthusiasts of exceptional watchmaking.

Marking a significant milestone in Patek PhilippeтАЩs journey in China, the Maison in Beijing is comparable to the Patek Philippe Salons in Geneva, London, and Paris, both in status and function. It offers an unparalleled setting where guests can immerse themselves in the brandтАЩs timeless artistry and unwavering commitment to service.

Every visit is an invitation to experience the enduring values that have defined Patek Philippe since 1839.

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMaisons
user_info.Images[6].Caption:
The opening of Maison Patek Philippe in Shanghai in 2012 led to the expansion of the Service Center at Yifeng Galleria, with an independent space of nearly 1,000 square meters, perfectly equipped to accommodate 30 employees.

In September 2013, Patek Philippe reaffirmed its long-term investment and confidence in the Chinese market by inaugurating the Patek Philippe Institute Shanghai тАФ its first training center outside Geneva. This institution was created to recruit and train local apprentices, ensuring that after-sales service meets the strict quality standards established by the Manufacture, in full compliance with the Patek Philippe Seal.

Today, the Shanghai Service Center remains one of only two Patek Philippe Authorized Service Centers in mainland China, a testament to the brandтАЩs enduring pursuit of excellence.

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMaisons
user_info.Images[7].Caption:
The Maison Patek Philippe Shanghai enjoys a prime location along the scenic Huangpu River, surrounded by Victorian and neoclassical buildings. This site holds a special place in ShanghaiтАЩs history, marking the cityтАЩs early development. The name тАЬMaisonтАЭ reflects its prestigious status, while тАЬYuanтАЭ (ц║Р) in Chinese means тАЬoriginтАЭ in English and signifies both its geographical origins and its role as a source of culture and heritage. The building itself, originally the residence of the British Consul General, carries a distinguished legacy.

The interior of Maison Patek Philippe Shanghai embodies the elegance of the Napol├йon III style and recreates the refined atmosphere of Patek PhilippeтАЩs Geneva Salon.

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMaisons
user_info.Images[8].Caption:
In 2005, Patek Philippe opened its first boutique in China in the historic Bund area of Shanghai. As Patek PhilippeтАЩs presence in China continued to flourish, a deeper appreciation for the brand grew within the country. In response, Patek Philippe created a warm and welcoming area, open to all watch aficionados.

As a landmark of Patek PhilippeтАЩs 20-year journey in China, the Maison in Shanghai holds a unique position in the world, comparable to the Patek Philippe Salons in Geneva, London, and Paris - presenting the brandтАЩs collections in an exclusive setting, combined with an unwavering dedication to service.

Each visit offers guests the opportunity to experience the emotional connection that has defined Patek Philippe since its founding in 1839.

#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeMaisons
user_info.Images[9].Caption: Since 1995, the Paris Salons have stood at Place Vend├┤me, the cityтАЩs emblematic hub for 'haute horlogerie' and 'haute joaillerie'. With their Art Deco elegance, the Salons harmonize beautifully with the historic architecture of this iconic Parisian square.\n\n#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeSalons
user_info.Images[10].Caption: The Art Deco-style is reflected throughout the Paris Salons, in harmony between tradition and innovation. The Salons present the same combination of classicism and modernity as that of the Patek Philippe Salons in Geneva, with the same marriage of noble materials such as marble, alabaster and rosewood or maple wood. However, the space remains its own with particular emphasis on artistic ironwork, perfectly in line with the тАЬGrand Si├иcleтАЭ architecture of Place Vend├┤me.\n\n#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeSalons
user_info.Images[11].Caption: The City of Light has a special significance for Patek Philippe. In 1844, Antoine Norbert de Patek first met Jean Adrien Philippe, in Paris, and a piece of history was made. Over a century later, in 1986, Philippe Stern (then President of Patek Philippe) opened the first Salons outside Geneva on Avenue Montaigne, marking a significant milestone in the companyтАЩs history. In 1995, they moved to Place Vend├┤me, ParisтАЩ most emblematic landmark for 'haute horlogerie' and 'haute joaillerie', where it has remained ever since.\n\n#PatekTime #PatekPhilippeSalons

Because of MaтАЩs Blessings I fell towards the mountain side and didnтАЩt get even a scratch. My eyes closed and I fainted. Just then my father and his friends came and took me in a car to a hospital. There the doctor gave me an injection and  medicine. In a few hours I became conscious. Then we all left for Kainchi and reached the Kainchi Ashram by evening around 6:00p.m. Ma was standing in front of our room in the verandah. user_info.Images[4].Caption: ЁЯХЙя╕П рд░рд╛рдо рд░рд╛рдо , Maharaj addressed the murti at the Hanuman temple in Rambag, Allahabad, as the тАЬController General.тАЭ One day Sri Ma was at the temple with Maharaj and saw an old woman climbing the stairs with great difficulty to have the darshan of Hanuman, who was on the first floor. When the back walls collapsed, the murti descended to the ground floor in a standing position, as if Hanuman-ji had been carefully placed there. The murti was not damaged at all. user_info.Images[6].Caption: ЁЯХЙя╕П рд░рд╛рдо рд░рд╛рдо , My Mother was a devotee of Hanuman ji from childhood; she worshiped Him and had complete faith in Him. Whenever she had any problem she would tell Hanuman Ji. Perhaps it was because of this that she got Hanuman Ji, in the form of Maharaj, in her life. One day, lja asked Maharaj. тАЬeveryone calls you Hanuman ji, are you Hanuman? Why canтАЩt I see?тАЭ He answered, тАЬthere is a stone in your eye.тАЭ Now what did that mean? user_info.Images[7].Caption: ЁЯХЙя╕П рд░рд╛рдо рд░рд╛рдо , SUIL: When we went to Kainchi on the bus, we passed this house, and I went, тАЬOh, I want to stay there.тАЭ It turned out the owners of that house, both doctors in Nainital, were from Scotland, from my same town. That was the house I wound up staying in. The flower garden there was almost like a nursery. You could go down the back road through all of those flowers, through the rivers, through the mountains, and end up at the rear of the ashram. One morning I collected a bunch of flowers and came in through the back of the ashram. It turned out everyone had been jaoed except Larry and Girija. Maharajji called me over, and I gave him the flowers. What I heard him say to me, and what stayed in my mind for a long time, was, тАЬEvery flower blooms in its own time.тАЭ I didnтАЩt have a very strong identity, and I wasnтАЩt really sure who I was in all of this. It was the first time I was living alone, in the mountains with the monkeys. So when he said that statement about all flowers blooming in their own time, I felt relief knowing that I didnтАЩt have to be concerned if I was okay, if I was going to be a saint or not. Many years later at a bandhara I met Larry again. We were remembering that story with the flowers, and what Larry remembered was a completely different story. He had heard Maharajji say that all the flowers bloom at the same time. Really? I was sure he said in their own time. We talked about which version we liked better. I was glad that I heard my version, because that was very helpful in my whole journey. Even today, that idea that the timing of everything is really perfect, that there is a perfection in everything, and as the flowers bloom so shall we . . . ThereтАЩs been an ease that came in that story, and that was something I would never forget, in a very simple statement that other people heard differently, of course. We love that. - Love  Everyone by Parvati Markus maтАЩam , рд╕рд┐рдпрд╛ рд░рд╛рдо ЁЯМ╕

ЁЯХЙя╕П рд░рд╛рдо рд░рд╛рдо , The inauguration of the temple was to be celebrated in the most fitting manner, with pujas, havans, and prasad for everyone. The news
spread over a very large part of that area and people started coming. Everyone worked with a missionary zeal, and was convinced that their
preparations for the bhandara, which was soon to begin, were faultless. There was a sense of jubilation in having managed a difficult task,
and a few of them started speculating about the laurels that were awaiting them.
When Babaji arrived that evening, everyone joined in giving him an account of the work that had been completed. Every detail was given.
The prasad that had been prepared was enough to feed any unknown number of visitors. They then took Babaji around to see for himself all
that had been described. Babaji was pleased, and sat and listened with great satisfaction as they talked about their arrangements for feeding
people. Then, as if to get a minor clarification, he wanted to know on what they were going to serve the food. It was as if people who had
been going along, merrymaking on the road, suddenly got pushed into a ditch. Not one of them had remembered to get leaf plates!
What could be done at this short notice? People had started gathering, and feeding was to start within a few hours. There was no market
nearby. Haldwani and Bareilly were far away and the markets there would be closed for the night. It was hard to accept that a big engine
could not start if even a small part of strategic importance was missing. Gone was the cheer and jubilationтАФeveryone was motionless. One
could imagine, on a much larger scale, how the monkeys had sat on the shore of the sea after losing all hope of success in their search for
Sita.
Babaji sat silently with them. Seeing him like that, many became disturbed and started making all kinds of speculations about his silence. It
was his bhandara. They had been pushed into it by him. They were there only because of him, but now that they were faced with such a
crisis, he was sitting indifferently. They might be responsible, but why should they be punished when he could remove their crisis? - Continued in Comments
user_info.Images[9].Caption: ЁЯХЙя╕П рд░рд╛рдо рд░рд╛рдо , I heard Krishna Das sing тАЬMere GurudevтАЭ for the first time some sixteen years ago when I attended a Reiki seminar. My life was a mess. I felt sad, depressed, and anxious all the time, and I was consumed by anger from my child-hood. When I heard his voice, I felt something shift in me for the first time in years. Of course, I attributed my feeling of relief to my Reiki teacher, but I kept listening to Krishna Das and suddenly chants from my childhood started coming back to me. I remembered that my grandma used to chant every day. In January 2015, I attended a workshop that Krishna Das conducted in Mumbai. I had always seen a picture of Baba whenever Krishna Das sang, but I had no curiosity to know more about the man in the picture. A few days later, as is my practice each morning, I walked around a park while chanting along with Krishna Das on my phone. Suddenly my phone pinged and MaharajiтАЩs photo popped up. I could not stop looking at him. I felt like I had definitely seen him before. A few days later I started getting attracted to the Hanuman Chalisa, which gave me such solace. I live with my husband and son. My mother-in-law, who was bedridden for the last five years of her life, also lived with us. She was the kindest, most loving person I had ever met, and I viewed her as my mother. I started chanting the Chalisa for her and she said that it brought her such peace. We chanted together every morning and evening. One day I was walking in the morning, chanting as usual. The park in which I walk has a Hanuman Temple. I passed the temple and suddenly, from the opposite direction, there was a huge beautiful golden monkey walking right towards me, looking straight at me. His eyes were almost human. This is not the kind of monkey we see in a city like Mumbai. - Continued In Comments Part 1 & 2
user_info.Images[10].Caption: ЁЯХЙя╕П рд░рд╛рдо рд░рд╛рдо , We think we are running after the Guru, but he is actually running after us. Why does he do it?  He is not fond of your money he is not fond of the sweet or nice things you talk about him; he is not fond of the publicity you can make about him. It is out of sheer grace, out of sheer kindness. You must know that a sage or a saint has got the whole wealth of the world at his disposal. He has got no needs, no requirements of his own. He doesnтАЩt worry about food, clothes, money, nothing of the sort. A Guru is there to carry the big loads or burdens of his disciples. This is what the Guru goes on doing, giving and giving and giving to you. That giving we cannot call charity, which is a word that comes from our family references, our business life, our day-to-day life. A gift or charity is made to one from whom we have received something in the past or hope to get something in the future. When a gift is given, the relationship between the person making the gift and receiving it comes to be one superior and the other inferior. Somebody who goes on receiving charity, getting gifts, can never himself be very proud or very happy. But in the case of grace, anybody who has got the grace of God feels himself so elevated. тАЬOh, I have become something divine. I have been elevated.тАЭ So when the grace of the Guru comes, its purpose is to elevate, to raise and lift people. Now we know that a sage or a saint does not want anything, he has no need of his own, but still, out of grace, he makes you work for him, makes you give to him. A Guru comes to have a claim not only on your physical labor and exertion, but also on the working of your mind and on every possession. Tan- man-dhan [body-mind-wealth]. Your Guru can claim it all. In India, when you go to a temple and the priest performs a puja or any kind of prayer or ceremony, you must pay him a fee. You might also give prasad, rich clothes and ornaments to the deity, but if you donтАЩt pay the priest, your worship is not complete. Similarly, a Guru is taking a lump of clay and turning it into something permanent and beautiful and abiding. - Continued in comments part 1 , 2 & 3

user_info.Images[11].Caption:
APPEAL
┬а
On the evening of Thursday 17th October a number of masked people burgled my home in the Castle Eden area in the North East.
┬а
They escaped with jewellery, other valuables and a good deal of personal items. Many of those items have real sentimental value for me and my family.┬а They are irreplaceable.
┬а
This is an appeal for any help in finding these people who carried out this act.
┬а
By far the worst thing about this crime is that it was carried out whilst my wife and 2 young children were in the house. Thankfully, none of my family came to any physical harm. Understandably, however, the experience has had an impact on their emotional and mental state. All we can think about is how much worse this situation could have been.
┬а
I am releasing photographs of some of the stolen items - which I hope may be easily identified - in the hope that we can find the people who are responsible for this.
┬а
Although we have lost cherished possessions, to be clear, my sole motivation in sharing these photographs is not the recovery of material items. It is to catch the people who did this.
┬а
Please come forward and contact Durham Constabulary on 101 quoting crime reference CRI00575927 if you think that you have any relevant information.
┬а
Finally, I want to say thank you to the police service. Both now and whilst I was away in Pakistan, their support for my family has been outstanding.┬а They continue to work incredibly hard in trying to find these people.
┬а
тЬМя╕П Stokes Fam
